T1  - Toward a Model of Organizations as Interpretation Systems
AU  - Daft, Richard L.
AU  - Weick, Karl E.
Y1  - 1984/04/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1984.4277657
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1984.4277657
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 284
EP  - 295
VL  - 9
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A comparative model of organizations as interpretation systems is proposed. The model describes four interpretation modes: enacting, discovering, undirected viewing, and conditioned viewing. Each mode is determined by (1) management's beliefs about the environment and (2) organizational intrusiveness. Interpretation modes are hypothesized to be associated with organizational differences in environmental scanning, equivocality reduction, strategy, and decision making.
AB  - A comparative model of organizations as interpretation systems is proposed. The model describes four interpretation modes: enacting, discovering, undirected viewing, and conditioned viewing. Each mode is determined by (1) management's beliefs about the environment and (2) organizational intrusiveness. Interpretation modes are hypothesized to be associated with organizational differences in environmental scanning, equivocality reduction, strategy, and decision making.
