TY  - JOUR
T1  - Treating Progress Functions as a Managerial Opportunity
AU  - Dutton, John M.
AU  - Thomas, Annie
Y1  - 1984/04/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1984.4277639
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1984.4277639
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 235
EP  - 247
VL  - 9
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Use of progress functions in strategic planning has led to the principle that firms can expect continuous cost improvements with cumulative output. But finding policies that result in continuous cost improvements requires a better understanding of the dynamics underlying firms' progress functions. This paper draws on more than 200 empirical and theoretical studies of progress functions in industrial engineering, economics, and management. Factors causing progress fall into four categories that vary in origin (exogenous or endogenous) and in type (autonomous or induced).
AB  - Use of progress functions in strategic planning has led to the principle that firms can expect continuous cost improvements with cumulative output. But finding policies that result in continuous cost improvements requires a better understanding of the dynamics underlying firms' progress functions. This paper draws on more than 200 empirical and theoretical studies of progress functions in industrial engineering, economics, and management. Factors causing progress fall into four categories that vary in origin (exogenous or endogenous) and in type (autonomous or induced).
